(* ===================================================================
   III-GRAMMAR.bnf — The Formal Grammar of III
   Document Identity:    A2 / The Grammar
   Canonical Hash Slot:  R1.A2
   Version:              1.0 — Final & Sealed
   Date:                 2026-05-03
   Authority:            Canonical. The SELF compiler `telosc-σ` MUST parse
                         every valid III source using exactly the productions
                         in this document. Any deviation is a conformance
                         failure (see §13 and III-CONFORMANCE.md C-2 / C-LEX-FROZEN).
   Parent Architecture:  Language-as-Operating-System (Language-as-OS)
   Predecessor:          A1 III-LEXICON.md (R1.A1)
   Successors:           A3 III-TYPES.md, A4 III-EFFECTS.md, A5 III-CYCLES.md,
                         A6 III-HEXAD.md, A7 III-PHASES.md, A8 III-SANCTUM.md,
                         A9 III-TRINITY.md, A10 III-MODULES.md,
                         B1 III-CATALYST.md, B2 III-FEDERATION.md,
                         B3 III-CONFORMANCE.md, C1 III-ABI.md,
                         IDX III-INDEX.md.
   =================================================================== *)


(* ===================================================================
   §0. PREAMBLE
   =================================================================== *)

(*
   This grammar is the formal substitution invariant of III.

   III's grammar is not "C with extra syntax." It is the minimal formal
   system capable of expressing:

     - Witnessed, reversible, phase-polymorphic effects as first-class
       citizens (`cycle name(p) -> T @ring(...) { forward { ... }
       inverse { ... } }`).
     - Six-trit asymmetric safety hexads as type modifiers
       (`u64 @hexad(MSR_WRITE)`), with the catastrophic-operation hexads
       being literally untypable.
     - Möbius self-reference and Catalyst-driven runtime syntax extension
       (`mobius_candidate ... @candidate_for_promotion`,
       `promote { ... }`).
     - A persistent witnessed Narrative Self
       (`narrative { core_identity: ..., goal_hierarchy: ... }`).
     - Linear, glyph-bound capabilities (`Cap<write, 0x1000..0x2000>`).
     - Wavefront concurrency as the *only* effect sequencing
       (`wavefront { ... } until quiescent`).
     - Constitutional ceilings, Trinity gates, sanctum blocks, and metal
       escape hatches as first-class language primitives.
     - Bricking operations as syntactically impossible — no production
       in this grammar can introduce a hexad-tag that lies outside the
       144-byte reachability bitmap `xii_asym_reach6`.

   Every production in this document corresponds to exactly one
   enumerator in `iii_ast_kind_t` (see §11).

   The SELF compiler MUST parse III source using the productions
   defined here, and only those productions. Any deviation — added
   production, removed production, changed associativity, new keyword
   outside Catalyst promotion — is a conformance failure (C-LEX-FROZEN
   in III-CONFORMANCE.md, also restated as C-2 here).

   The mhash of the canonical UTF-8 text of this file (R1.A2) is
   embedded in every compiled module's closure root. Two source files
   parsed by two implementations of this grammar must produce
   byte-identical AST root mhashes if and only if those sources differ
   only in whitespace, comment text, or modifier order
   (per the canonicalization rules in §10).
*)


(* ===================================================================
   §1. CONFORMANCE & SEALING
   =================================================================== *)

(*
   §1.1 Sealing Discipline

   This document is sealed against the C:\CHARIOT closure of 2026-05-03.
   The grammar is frozen. The only legal extension pathway is the
   Catalyst's reserved-slot mechanism (§13 below; III-LEXICON.md §14;
   III-CATALYST.md §2). No pull requests. No grammar working group.
   No language committee. Only mathematical saturation in OBSERVATORY +
   Trinity-gated witnessed promotion + DRTM relaunch.

   §1.2 Substitution Invariant

   Every conformant III implementation parses every valid III source
   using exactly the productions defined here. Two conformant
   implementations on the same canonical input produce AST trees
   that, when serialized to canonical AST form (see III-MODULES.md §1),
   yield byte-identical mhashes.

   §1.3 The SELF Compiler Requirement

   At Stage 4 self-host (III-SANCTUM.md §1, seal_id 9), the SELF
   compiler `telosc-σ` parses III source using the productions here.
   The SELF compiler's own source is written in III; that source must
   be parseable under this grammar. If `telosc-σ`'s source fails to
   parse under an implementation of this grammar, the implementation
   is non-conformant (C-LEX-SELF in III-CONFORMANCE.md).

   §1.4 The BOOT Compiler Requirement

   The BOOT compiler `telosc-0` (hand-written C in
   `COMPILER/BOOT/parse.{h,c}`) parses every III source produced
   during Stages 0..4 using these productions. BOOT is a recursive-
   descent parser, NIH-extreme: no Bison, no ANTLR, no tree-sitter,
   no parser combinator library.
*)


(* ===================================================================
   §2. NOTATION CONVENTIONS
   =================================================================== *)

(*
   The grammar is expressed in a hand-rolled EBNF-style notation:

     ::=        production-defines
     |          production-alternative
     ?          zero or one
     *          zero or more
     +          one or more
     ()         grouping
     'literal'  terminal token-text (matches a `KEYWORD`, `MODIFIER`,
                `OPERATOR`, or `PUNCT` token whose canonical text
                equals the literal)
     UPPERCASE  terminal token-kind (e.g., IDENT, INT_LIT, MHASH_LIT)
                from the lexer (see III-LEXICON.md §3.1)
     lowercase  non-terminal (a production defined elsewhere in this
                document)

   The productions are presented in five groups:

     §4 Module-level productions (the top of the AST).
     §5 Item productions (declarations within a module).
     §6 Type productions.
     §7 Statement productions.
     §8 Expression productions (with explicit precedence climbing).
     §9 Pattern productions.

   Disambiguation rules and associativity tables are in §10. The AST
   kind enumerator (`iii_ast_kind_t`) is in §11.

   This notation is hand-rolled, intentionally simpler than ISO 14977
   (Standard EBNF) — III rejects standards-body templates per the NIH
   discipline (III-LEXICON.md §1.2 C-LEX-NIH).
*)


(* ===================================================================
   §3. LEXICAL TOKENS (REFERENCE)
   =================================================================== *)

(*
   The terminal token-kinds used by this grammar are defined in
   III-LEXICON.md §3.1. The canonical kinds, restated here for
   convenience:

     KEYWORD          — one of 47 reserved words (III-LEXICON.md §4)
     MODIFIER         — one of 19 `@`-prefixed annotations
                        (III-LEXICON.md §5)
     OPERATOR         — one of 23 sovereign-calculus operators
                        (III-LEXICON.md §6)
     PUNCT            — one of 25 ASCII-or-comparison punctuators
                        (III-LEXICON.md §7)
     IDENT            — an ASCII identifier (III-LEXICON.md §8)
     INT_LIT          — integer literal (III-LEXICON.md §9.1)
     MHASH_LIT        — exactly 64 hex digits prefixed by 0x
                        (III-LEXICON.md §9.3)
     TRIT_LIT         — NEG / ZERO / POS or numeric trit forms
                        (III-LEXICON.md §9.4)
     HEXAD_LIT        — parenthesized 6-tuple of trits
                        (III-LEXICON.md §9.5)
     Q14_LIT          — Q14 fixed-point literal
                        (III-LEXICON.md §9.6)
     STRING_LIT       — UTF-8 string literal (III-LEXICON.md §9.7.1)
     BYTE_STRING_LIT  — byte-string literal (III-LEXICON.md §9.7.2)
     RAW_STRING_LIT   — raw string literal (III-LEXICON.md §9.7.3)
     HEX_STRING_LIT   — hex string literal (III-LEXICON.md §9.7.4)
     DOC_COMMENT      — documentation comment (III-LEXICON.md §10.3)
     EOF              — end-of-input sentinel

   Throughout this document, when a production references a literal
   keyword like 'cycle', it matches the KEYWORD token whose text is
   exactly "cycle". When it references a literal modifier like
   '@hexad', it matches the MODIFIER token whose text is exactly
   "@hexad". When it references a literal operator or punctuator, it
   matches the OPERATOR or PUNCT token whose text is exactly that
   sequence.
*)


(* ===================================================================
   §4. MODULE-LEVEL PRODUCTIONS
   =================================================================== *)

start                   ::= module EOF

module                  ::= 'module' qualified_name module_attr* import* item*

qualified_name          ::= IDENT ('.' IDENT)*

module_attr             ::= '@closure' '(' MHASH_LIT ')'
                          | '@ring' '(' ring_set ')'
                          | '@plan_anchor' '(' IDENT ')'
                          | '@version' '(' STRING_LIT ')'
                          | '@tier' '(' tier_name ')'
                          | doc_attached

import                  ::= 'use' qualified_name import_attr*

import_attr             ::= '@closure' '(' MHASH_LIT ')'
                          | '@ring' '(' ring_set ')'
                          | '@tier' '(' tier_name ')'

item                    ::= cycle_decl
                          | function_decl
                          | type_decl
                          | mobius_candidate_decl
                          | schema_decl
                          | narrative_decl
                          | const_decl
                          | extern_decl
                          | doc_attached

doc_attached            ::= DOC_COMMENT

(*
   Module-level commentary

   - `module` is the top declaration. Every III source file is a
     module; there are no anonymous compilation units.
   - The module's `qualified_name` is the source-level identifier
     used in `use` paths; the module's *identity* is its
     `closure_root` (SHA-256 of canonical source per III-LEXICON.md
     §2.5), set automatically by the SELF compiler and optionally
     pinned by `@closure(...)` for provenance auditing.
   - `@plan_anchor` binds the module to a section of an external
     architectural plan document (used by `iii-attest` and the
     OBSERVATORY's plan-coverage schema).
   - `@tier` at module level sets the default replication tier for
     all values declared in the module (overridable per-binding).
   - `import_attr @closure(...)` is the *content-addressed pin*: the
     resolver refuses to load a module whose canonical mhash differs
     from the pinned value (`MOD-RES-001 closure mismatch` —
     III-MODULES.md §3).
*)


(* ===================================================================
   §5. ITEM PRODUCTIONS
   =================================================================== *)

(*
   Items are top-level declarations within a module. The grammar
   admits seven item kinds: cycle, fn, type, mobius_candidate,
   schema, narrative, const, extern (one of which — narrative — is
   semantically restricted to one-per-module; see III-MODULES.md).
*)

(* ----- 5.1 Cycle declaration (the universal verb) ----- *)

cycle_decl              ::= 'cycle' IDENT '(' param_list? ')'
                            '->' type
                            cycle_modifier*
                            '{'
                                forward_block
                                inverse_block?
                            '}'

forward_block           ::= 'forward' '{' statement_list '}'

inverse_block           ::= 'inverse' '{' statement_list '}'

cycle_modifier          ::= '@ring' '(' ring_set ')'
                          | '@hexad' '(' hexad_designator ')'
                          | '@safety' '(' hexad_designator ')'
                          | '@tier' '(' tier_name ')'
                          | '@epoch' '(' epoch_value ')'
                          | '@plan_anchor' '(' IDENT ')'
                          | '@admits_caps' '(' cap_list ')'
                          | '@prerequisites' '(' identifier_list ')'
                          | '@replicates' '(' replication_policy ')'
                          | '@irreversible'
                          | '@pure'
                          | '@witness_elide'
                          | '@hot_path'
                          | '@chronos_bypass'
                          | '@sanctum_only'
                          | '@mobius_coherence' '(' coherence_expr ')'
                          | '@candidate_for_promotion'
                          | '@epoch_bridge'

(*
   Cycle-declaration commentary

   - The `forward { ... }` block is mandatory. It is the body the
     programmer writes.
   - The `inverse { ... }` block is *mechanically derived* by SID
     (III-EFFECTS.md §3, III-CYCLES.md §3). It may be omitted in
     source; the compiler emits the SID-derived inverse. It may be
     written explicitly only when SID's classification is incomplete
     (e.g., a cycle that interacts with an `@irreversible` operation
     and needs a manually authored Compromise-tier inverse).
   - If `@irreversible` is set, the inverse is fixed to
     `Compromise<MEDIUM>` (or `Compromise<LOW>` per safety-level
     resolution in III-EFFECTS.md §1.2) and an explicit
     `inverse { ... }` block is rejected (`PARSE-CYCLE-001
     irreversible cycle cannot have explicit inverse`).
   - If `@pure` is set, the cycle has zero effect; SID emits a
     no-op inverse, and the compiler may elide the runtime witness
     iff `@witness_elide` is also set (otherwise a pure cycle still
     emits a witness for audit-spine continuity).
*)


(* ----- 5.2 Function declaration (phase-polymorphic) ----- *)

function_decl           ::= 'fn' IDENT generic_param_list?
                            '(' param_list? ')'
                            '->' type
                            function_modifier*
                            '{' statement_list '}'

generic_param_list      ::= '<' generic_param (',' generic_param)* '>'

generic_param           ::= IDENT (':' type_constraint)?

type_constraint         ::= 'Hexad' | 'Phase' | 'Tier' | 'Epoch' | type

function_modifier       ::= '@ring' '(' ring_set ')'
                          | '@hexad' '(' hexad_designator ')'
                          | '@safety' '(' hexad_designator ')'
                          | '@pure'
                          | '@sanctum_only'
                          | '@hot_path'
                          | '@witness_elide'
                          | '@chronos_bypass'
                          | '@epoch_bridge'

param_list              ::= param (',' param)*

param                   ::= IDENT ':' type

(*
   Function commentary

   - `fn` declares a phase-polymorphic function.
   - A function may declare generic parameters constrained by
     `Hexad`, `Phase`, `Tier`, `Epoch`, or any concrete `type`. The
     constraint system is the type-system contract from
     III-TYPES.md §4–§9.
   - A function with `@ring(R-2, R-1, R0, R3)` produces four lowerings
     (one per ring) per III-PHASES.md §2; the compiler synthesizes
     the marshalling.
   - Unlike a `cycle`, a `fn` does not declare a `forward { } /
     inverse { }` pair — non-cycle functions do not produce
     witnessed reductions on every call. They may still emit
     witnesses if they invoke cycles internally (which they
     usually do).
*)


(* ----- 5.3 Type declaration ----- *)

type_decl               ::= 'type' IDENT generic_param_list? '=' type type_modifier*

type_modifier           ::= '@ring' '(' ring_set ')'
                          | '@hexad' '(' hexad_designator ')'
                          | '@safety' '(' hexad_designator ')'
                          | '@tier' '(' tier_name ')'
                          | '@epoch' '(' epoch_value ')'
                          | '@cap' '(' cap_perm ',' range? ')'
                          | '@sanctum_only'
                          | '@irreversible'
                          | '@pure'
                          | '@closure' '(' MHASH_LIT ')'
                          | '@phys'
                          | '@gpa' '(' IDENT ')'
                          | '@uva' '(' IDENT ')'

(*
   Type declaration commentary

   `type` declarations introduce named type aliases. The right-hand
   `type` may carry modifiers; modifiers attach to the resulting
   alias and are inherited at every use-site (per III-TYPES.md §3).

   `@phys`, `@gpa(IDENT)`, `@uva(IDENT)` are address-space modifiers
   used in cross-ring memory typing (physical address vs guest
   physical vs user virtual). They are admitted by the lexer/parser
   and resolved by the type system (III-TYPES.md §4 ring-typed
   values).
*)


(* ----- 5.4 Möbius candidate declaration ----- *)

mobius_candidate_decl   ::= 'mobius_candidate' IDENT
                            '(' param_list? ')' '->' type
                            mobius_candidate_modifier*
                            '{' forward_block '}'

mobius_candidate_modifier
                        ::= '@hexad' '(' hexad_designator ')'
                          | '@safety' '(' hexad_designator ')'
                          | '@candidate_for_promotion'
                          | '@plan_anchor' '(' IDENT ')'
                          | '@mobius_coherence' '(' coherence_expr ')'
                          | '@hot_path'

(*
   mobius_candidate commentary

   `mobius_candidate` declares a function that is *eligible* for
   Catalyst promotion (III-CATALYST.md §2). It carries only a
   `forward { ... }` body — there is no inverse declaration because
   a candidate has not yet been admitted to the cycle table; if the
   Catalyst promotes it, SID derives the inverse at promotion time.

   Every `mobius_candidate` must carry exactly one of `@hexad` or
   `@safety` (these are aliases per III-LEXICON.md §5.2) — the
   candidate's safety profile is the basis for hexad-admissibility
   evaluation. Candidates with hexads outside `xii_asym_reach6` are
   rejected at parse time (`PARSE-MOB-001 candidate hexad outside
   reachable set`); see III-HEXAD.md §5 (Dynamic Hexads) for the
   one path by which a previously unreachable hexad may become
   reachable.
*)


(* ----- 5.5 OBSERVATORY schema declaration ----- *)

schema_decl             ::= 'schema' IDENT '=' 'OBSERVATORY' '{'
                                schema_field (',' schema_field)*
                            '}'

schema_field            ::= IDENT ':' schema_field_type

schema_field_type       ::= 'Welford'
                          | 'Hoeffding' '(' 'epsilon' ':' Q14_LIT
                                            ',' 'delta' ':' Q14_LIT ')'
                          | 'Multinomial' '(' 'k' ':' INT_LIT ')'
                          | 'Wilson' '(' 'p' ':' Q14_LIT ')'
                          | 'Poisson' '(' 'lambda' ':' Q14_LIT ')'
                          | 'Coupon' '(' 'n' ':' INT_LIT ')'
                          | 'CMSketch' '(' 'depth' ':' INT_LIT
                                          ',' 'width' ':' INT_LIT ')'
                          | 'OrderStat' '(' 'k' ':' INT_LIT ')'
                          | 'Nyquist' '(' 'rate' ':' INT_LIT ')'
                          | 'ESS' '(' 'tau' ':' Q14_LIT ')'
                          | 'Heaps' '(' 'beta' ':' Q14_LIT ')'
                          | 'RuleOfThree'
                          | 'TDigest' '(' 'compression' ':' INT_LIT ')'
                          | 'Histogram' '(' 'k' ':' INT_LIT ')'
                          | IDENT

(*
   Schema commentary

   `schema` declarations introduce typed statistical accumulators
   bound to OBSERVATORY (III-CATALYST.md §3). Each field is an
   element of the 12-family threshold library (Welford / Hoeffding /
   Multinomial / Wilson / Poisson / Coupon / CMSketch / OrderStat /
   Nyquist / ESS / Heaps / RuleOfThree, plus the auxiliary forms
   TDigest and Histogram).

   The trailing `IDENT` alternative admits user-defined accumulator
   kinds registered via Catalyst-promoted accumulator-class
   extension (III-CATALYST.md §3.1).
*)


(* ----- 5.6 Narrative declaration ----- *)

narrative_decl          ::= 'narrative' '{'
                                narrative_field (',' narrative_field)*
                            '}'

narrative_field         ::= 'core_identity'    ':' expr
                          | 'goal_hierarchy'   ':' expr
                          | 'recent_events'    ':' expr
                          | 'internal_state'   ':' expr
                          | 'open_questions'   ':' expr
                          | 'mission'          ':' expr
                          | 'epoch_seeded'     ':' expr

(*
   Narrative commentary

   `narrative` declarations are the cognitive-layer identity
   (III-CYCLES.md §6 — Self-Modifying Cycles, MNEME §13.3.2). Each
   module may declare at most one `narrative` block; the parser
   permits multiple in source but the type system rejects
   duplicates (`TYPE-NAR-001 multiple narrative declarations`).

   Each narrative_field's RHS is an expression (typically a
   `STRING_LIT` for `core_identity` and `mission`, a list literal
   for `goal_hierarchy` and `open_questions`, and a record literal
   for `internal_state`).
*)


(* ----- 5.7 Const declaration ----- *)

const_decl              ::= 'const' IDENT ':' type '=' expr type_modifier*

(*
   Const commentary

   `const` declares an immutable, compile-time-evaluated binding.
   The expression on the RHS must be a constant expression
   (III-TYPES.md §10 — only literals, content-addressed values,
   and `@pure` function calls are admitted in constant context).

   `const` is reserved as a contextual keyword; it is *not* in the
   47-keyword list (III-LEXICON.md §4) because it appears only at
   item-level introduction. The lexer admits it as a lexer-level
   IDENT and the parser context-disambiguates: an IDENT 'const'
   that begins a top-level item is the const-introducer; elsewhere
   it is an ordinary identifier. *)

(* Note: the `const` form above is provisional — the canonical
   surface for compile-time-evaluated bindings is `let X: T = e`
   with `@pure` annotation. The `const` keyword may be promoted to
   the keyword list in a future Catalyst extension if the
   contextual-keyword approach proves error-prone. As of R1.A2,
   `let` (with `@pure` if needed) is the canonical form, and
   `const` is admitted at item-level only as an alias. *)


(* ----- 5.8 Extern declaration ----- *)

extern_decl             ::= 'extern' '@abi' '(' abi_name ')' '{'
                                extern_item*
                            '}'

abi_name                ::= 'c-msvc-x64'

extern_item             ::= 'fn' IDENT '(' extern_param_list? ')' '->' extern_type ';'
                          | 'type' IDENT '=' extern_type ';'
                          | DOC_COMMENT

extern_param_list       ::= extern_param (',' extern_param)*

extern_param            ::= IDENT ':' extern_type

extern_type             ::= 'i8' | 'i16' | 'i32' | 'i64'
                          | 'u8' | 'u16' | 'u32' | 'u64'
                          | 'f32' | 'f64'
                          | 'bool'
                          | '*' extern_type        (* raw pointer *)
                          | '&' extern_type        (* reference  *)
                          | '[' extern_type ';' INT_LIT ']'  (* fixed array *)
                          | IDENT                  (* extern-declared type *)

(*
   Extern commentary

   `extern @abi(c-msvc-x64) { ... }` is the *only* legal cross-language
   bridge in III. (See III-ABI.md.) It is a witnessed, round-tripping
   form: every extern call is a cycle whose forward invokes the C
   function and whose inverse is `Compromise<MEDIUM>` (no general
   reverse-engineering of opaque C effects is possible). Calls into
   C from Ring -2 are forbidden (the type system rejects them);
   extern is ring-restricted to R0 and R3.

   `c-msvc-x64` is the only currently-defined ABI. Additional ABI
   names (e.g., `c-sysv-x64`, `vmrun-trampoline`, `magic-msr`,
   `ioctl`) are reserved for future Catalyst-promoted extensions per
   III-ABI.md §1.2.
*)


(* ===================================================================
   §6. TYPE PRODUCTIONS
   =================================================================== *)

type                    ::= base_type type_modifier*
                          | function_type
                          | tuple_type
                          | array_type

base_type               ::= primitive_type
                          | qualified_name generic_args?
                          | 'Cap' '<' cap_perm ',' range? '>'
                          | 'Cycle' '<' type_list '>'
                          | 'Reduction' '<' type_list '>'
                          | 'Glyph'
                          | 'Witness'
                          | 'Hexad'
                          | 'Phase'
                          | 'Epoch'
                          | 'WitnessedTime'
                          | 'Trit'
                          | 'TritAsym'
                          | 'Q14'
                          | 'Uncertainty' '<' type_list '>'
                          | 'CeilingMembership' '<' type '>'
                          | 'MöbiusCoherence' '<' Q14_LIT '>'
                          | 'Compromise' '<' compromise_tier '>'
                          | hole

primitive_type          ::= 'bool'
                          | 'u8' | 'u16' | 'u32' | 'u64'
                          | 'i8' | 'i16' | 'i32' | 'i64'
                          | 'f32' | 'f64'
                          | 'string'
                          | 'mhash'

function_type           ::= 'fn' '(' type_list? ')' '->' type type_modifier*

tuple_type              ::= '(' type (',' type)* ')'                (* arity ≥ 2; arity-1 is `(T,)` *)
                          | '(' type ',' ')'                        (* unit-tuple-of-T *)
                          | '(' ')'                                 (* unit *)

array_type              ::= '[' type ';' INT_LIT ']'

generic_args            ::= '<' type (',' type)* '>'

type_list               ::= type (',' type)*

hole                    ::= '?'                       (* type metavariable; see III-TYPES.md §9 *)

ring_set                ::= ring (',' ring)*

ring                    ::= 'R-2' | 'R-1' | 'R0' | 'R3'

tier_name               ::= 'transient'
                          | 'host_file'
                          | 'federation'
                          | 'constitutional'

replication_policy      ::= 'local'
                          | 'broadcast'
                          | 'quorum_3'
                          | 'quorum_5'

cap_perm                ::= 'read' | 'write' | 'exec' | 'cycle'

range                   ::= INT_LIT '..' INT_LIT
                          | MHASH_LIT '..' MHASH_LIT
                          | IDENT

cap_list                ::= IDENT (',' IDENT)*

identifier_list         ::= IDENT (',' IDENT)*

epoch_value             ::= INT_LIT
                          | 'current'

hexad_designator        ::= IDENT                                   (* named hexad *)
                          | HEXAD_LIT                               (* literal hexad *)

coherence_expr          ::= '≥' Q14_LIT
                          | '≤' Q14_LIT
                          | Q14_LIT

compromise_tier         ::= 'LOW' | 'MEDIUM' | 'HIGH'

(*
   Type-production commentary

   - `Reduction<F, I, W, H, P, E>` is the six-tuple effect type
     (III-TYPES.md §2). Most user code does not write `Reduction`
     explicitly; it is the lowered type of every `cycle`
     declaration.
   - `Cap<perm, range>` is linear by default and glyph-bound
     (III-TYPES.md §6); `range` admits integer ranges (memory
     addresses), mhash ranges (capability spaces), or IDENTs
     (named ranges declared elsewhere).
   - `Uncertainty<Domain, Confidence, OpenQuestions>` is the
     epistemic type (III-TYPES.md §7); it carries the system's own
     self-knowledge.
   - `CeilingMembership<S>` and `MöbiusCoherence<Q>` are
     Prop-typed predicates (III-TYPES.md §8) — they are erased at
     runtime and verified by the type checker.
   - `Compromise<TIER>` is the type of an irreversible operation's
     inverse; it has three inhabitants per the three compromise
     tiers in III-EFFECTS.md §1.2 (`Compromise<HIGH>` is itself
     uninhabited because no syntactic form admits to it; the type
     exists for completeness in the lattice).
*)


(* ===================================================================
   §7. STATEMENT PRODUCTIONS
   =================================================================== *)

statement_list          ::= statement*

statement               ::= let_stmt
                          | assign_stmt
                          | if_stmt
                          | match_stmt
                          | for_stmt
                          | while_stmt
                          | wavefront_stmt
                          | sanctum_stmt
                          | metal_stmt
                          | return_stmt
                          | promote_stmt
                          | explain_stmt
                          | propose_stmt
                          | negotiate_stmt
                          | reflect_stmt
                          | commit_stmt
                          | reverse_stmt
                          | ask_stmt
                          | effect_stmt
                          | block_stmt
                          | doc_attached

let_stmt                ::= 'let' IDENT (':' type)? '=' expr ';'

assign_stmt             ::= place_expr '=' expr ';'

place_expr              ::= IDENT
                          | place_expr '.' IDENT
                          | place_expr '[' expr ']'
                          | place_expr '::' IDENT

if_stmt                 ::= 'if' expr block_expr ('else' (if_stmt | block_expr))?

match_stmt              ::= 'match' expr '{' match_arm (',' match_arm)* ','? '}'

match_arm               ::= pattern ('if' expr)? '=>' (expr | block_expr)

for_stmt                ::= 'for' IDENT 'in' expr ('where' expr)? block_expr

while_stmt              ::= 'while' expr block_expr

wavefront_stmt          ::= 'wavefront' wavefront_modifier*
                            '{' statement_list '}'
                            'until' wavefront_terminator

wavefront_modifier      ::= '@hexad' '(' hexad_designator ')'
                          | '@safety' '(' hexad_designator ')'
                          | '@mobius_coherence' '(' coherence_expr ')'
                          | '@admits_caps' '(' cap_list ')'

wavefront_terminator    ::= 'quiescent'
                          | 'coherent' '(' coherence_expr ')'
                          | 'count' '(' INT_LIT ')'

sanctum_stmt            ::= 'sanctum_enter' '|' IDENT '|' '{' statement_list '}'

metal_stmt              ::= 'metal' metal_modifier* '{' raw_asm '}'

metal_modifier          ::= '@ring' '(' ring ')'
                          | '@admits_caps' '(' cap_list ')'

raw_asm                 ::= (* implementation-defined assembly text;
                               parsed but not type-checked. Each
                               assembly directive is one or more
                               source lines containing intel-syntax
                               x86-64 instructions, label definitions,
                               and `let`-bindings of register names
                               to III locals (e.g., `let rcx_in =
                               %rcx`). The exact assembly grammar is
                               specified in III-PHASES.md §3.5 and
                               handled by the assembly subparser. *) ;

return_stmt             ::= 'return' expr? ';'

promote_stmt            ::= 'promote' '{' statement_list '}'

explain_stmt            ::= 'explain' '(' expr (',' detail_level)? ')' ';'

propose_stmt            ::= 'propose' '{' propose_field (',' propose_field)* '}'

propose_field           ::= 'abstraction_name' ':' expr
                          | 'justification'    ':' expr
                          | 'expected_impact'  ':' expr
                          | 'risk_profile'     ':' expr
                          | 'reversibility'    ':' expr

negotiate_stmt          ::= 'negotiate' '(' negotiate_arg (',' negotiate_arg)* ')' ';'

negotiate_arg           ::= 'goal'                 ':' expr
                          | 'constraints'          ':' expr
                          | 'preferences'          ':' expr
                          | 'uncertainty_tolerance' ':' expr

reflect_stmt            ::= 'reflect' '(' reflect_target ')' ';'

reflect_target          ::= 'state'
                          | 'uncertainty'
                          | 'coherence'
                          | 'narrative'
                          | 'manifest'
                          | 'epoch'

commit_stmt             ::= 'commit' '(' commit_arg (',' commit_arg)* ')' ';'

commit_arg              ::= 'intent'              ':' expr
                          | 'witness_requirements' ':' expr
                          | 'human_confirmation'  ':' expr

reverse_stmt            ::= 'inverse' '.' 'replay' '(' expr (',' expr)? ')' ';'

ask_stmt                ::= 'uncertainty' '.' 'in' '(' expr ')' ';'
                          | 'narrative'   '.' 'reflect' '(' expr ')' ';'

effect_stmt             ::= expr ';'

block_stmt              ::= block_expr ';'

block_expr              ::= '{' statement_list expr? '}'

detail_level            ::= 'executive'
                          | 'technical'
                          | 'full_trace'
                          | 'formal'
                          | 'visual'

(*
   Statement-production commentary

   - `let X: T = e` is the canonical binding form. The type `T` may
     be omitted (bidirectional inference, III-TYPES.md §9 — Hole-N1).
   - `wavefront { ... } until <terminator>` is the *only* sequencer of
     effectful statements. A bare `;` separator is admitted by the
     grammar but it does *not* impose ordering — the type system
     refuses to admit two side-effecting statements in the same block
     unless the block is a `wavefront` (per III-CYCLES.md §1).
     Pure statements can be sequenced freely.
   - `wavefront_terminator` extends the prior draft (which only
     supported `quiescent`) to admit `coherent(Q)` (terminate when
     manifold coherence reaches Q) and `count(N)` (terminate after
     N composed effects). All terminators are SID-derivable
     (III-CYCLES.md §3.2 step 27).
   - `sanctum_enter |frame| { ... }` is the *only* path to Ring -2.
     The frame binding `IDENT` is the per-CPU sanctum frame handle;
     the lexical scope inside the block has `@sanctum_active`
     enabled, which enables the `sanctum.<seal_id>` method calls.
   - `metal { ... }` blocks contain raw x86-64 assembly. The asm
     subparser runs after the III parser and is specified in
     III-PHASES.md §3.5.
   - The cognitive primitives (`explain`, `propose`, `negotiate`,
     `reflect`, `commit`, `reverse`, `ask`) are first-class
     statements. They emit witnesses just like cycle invocations do.
   - `effect_stmt ::= expr ';'` allows an expression to stand alone
     as a statement (for its side effects); `block_stmt` similarly
     admits a block-expression as a statement.
*)


(* ===================================================================
   §8. EXPRESSION PRODUCTIONS (PRECEDENCE-CLIMBING GRAMMAR)
   =================================================================== *)

(*
   Expression precedence is given by the following layered grammar
   from the loosest-binding outermost (`expr_lvl_0`) to the
   tightest-binding innermost (`primary`). Higher levels admit lower
   levels as alternatives; the lower levels do not admit higher
   levels (which prevents left-recursion and produces a deterministic
   recursive-descent parse).

   Precedence levels (loose → tight):

     Level 0 — Cognitive (right-assoc)        ⟐⟐, ⟡⟡, ⟴⟴
     Level 1 — Catalyst / Observatory         ⊛, ⧄, ⧋, ⧇
     Level 2 — Federation / Amendment         ⟶, ⨁
     Level 3 — Ceiling / Trinity (right)       ⟁, ⟐
     Level 4 — Phase / Epoch                  ⟴, ⟵
     Level 5 — Cap / Coherence                ⧈, ⧗
     Level 6 — Additive (cycles, hexads)      ⊕, ⧉, +, -
     Level 7 — Multiplicative                 *, /, %, ⧊
     Level 8 — Comparison                     ==, !=, <, >, ≤, ≥
     Level 9 — Logical conjunction (none — III rejects && in favor
               of explicit `wavefront` composition)
     Level 10 — Materialize                   ⊗
     Level 11 — Unary postfix                 ⟡, ↻, ⟲⟲, ⟲
     Level 12 — Unary prefix                  - (numeric negation), ! (Trit-NOT)
     Level 13 — Call / Index / Field          (), [], ., ::
     Level 14 — Primary                       literals, identifiers, parens, blocks

   The grammar productions below implement precedence climbing
   directly: `expr_lvl_K` may contain operators of level K and any
   tighter-binding subexpression `expr_lvl_(K+1)`.
*)

expr                    ::= expr_lvl_0

expr_lvl_0              ::= expr_lvl_1 ( cognitive_op expr_lvl_1 )*

cognitive_op            ::= '⟐⟐' | '⟡⟡' | '⟴⟴'

expr_lvl_1              ::= expr_lvl_2 ( catalyst_op expr_lvl_2 )*

catalyst_op             ::= '⊛' | '⧄' | '⧋' | '⧇'

expr_lvl_2              ::= expr_lvl_3 ( federation_op expr_lvl_3 )*

federation_op           ::= '⟶' | '⨁'

expr_lvl_3              ::= expr_lvl_4 ( ceiling_op expr_lvl_4 )*

ceiling_op              ::= '⟁' | '⟐'

expr_lvl_4              ::= expr_lvl_5 ( phase_op expr_lvl_5 )*

phase_op                ::= '⟴' ring                                (* phase cross *)
                          | '⟵' '@epoch' '(' INT_LIT ')'            (* epoch bridge *)

expr_lvl_5              ::= expr_lvl_6 ( cap_op expr_lvl_6 )*

cap_op                  ::= '⧈' acquire_release
                          | '⧗' Q14_LIT
                          | '⧗' coherence_expr

acquire_release         ::= 'acquire' | 'release'

expr_lvl_6              ::= expr_lvl_7 ( additive_op expr_lvl_7 )*

additive_op             ::= '⊕' | '⧉' | '+' | '-'

expr_lvl_7              ::= expr_lvl_8 ( multiplicative_op expr_lvl_8 )*

multiplicative_op       ::= '*' | '/' | '%' | '⧊'

expr_lvl_8              ::= expr_lvl_10 ( comparison_op expr_lvl_10 )?

comparison_op           ::= '==' | '!=' | '<' | '>' | '≤' | '≥'

(* Level 9 is intentionally absent. III has no `&&` or `||`. Logical
   conjunction is expressed via Trit operations on Bool/Trit values
   or via explicit `wavefront`-composition. *)

expr_lvl_10             ::= expr_lvl_11 ( '⊗' 'glyph' )?            (* materialize *)

expr_lvl_11             ::= expr_lvl_12 postfix_op*

postfix_op              ::= '⟡'                                     (* witness emit *)
                          | '↻'                                     (* replay *)
                          | '⟲⟲'                                    (* full inverse replay *)
                          | '⟲'                                     (* inverse *)

expr_lvl_12             ::= prefix_op? expr_lvl_13

prefix_op               ::= '-' | '!'

expr_lvl_13             ::= primary call_index_field*

call_index_field        ::= '(' arg_list? ')'                       (* call *)
                          | '[' expr ']'                            (* index *)
                          | '.' IDENT                               (* field *)
                          | '::' IDENT                              (* path *)

arg_list                ::= arg (',' arg)*

arg                     ::= expr
                          | IDENT ':' expr                          (* named argument *)

primary                 ::= literal
                          | qualified_name
                          | '(' expr ')'
                          | tuple_literal
                          | record_literal
                          | array_literal
                          | block_expr
                          | cycle_invoke
                          | sanctum_invoke
                          | irpd_call
                          | hole

literal                 ::= INT_LIT
                          | MHASH_LIT
                          | TRIT_LIT
                          | HEXAD_LIT
                          | Q14_LIT
                          | STRING_LIT
                          | BYTE_STRING_LIT
                          | RAW_STRING_LIT
                          | HEX_STRING_LIT
                          | 'true'
                          | 'false'

tuple_literal           ::= '(' expr (',' expr)+ ')'

record_literal          ::= qualified_name '{' record_field (',' record_field)* '}'

record_field            ::= IDENT ':' expr

array_literal           ::= '[' expr (',' expr)* ']'
                          | '[' expr ';' INT_LIT ']'                (* repeated *)

cycle_invoke            ::= 'cycle_invoke' '(' IDENT (',' arg_list)? ')'

sanctum_invoke          ::= 'sanctum' '.' IDENT '(' arg_list? ')'

irpd_call               ::= 'irpd' '.' IDENT '(' arg_list? ')'

(*
   Expression-production commentary

   - The precedence ladder is total. Every legal III expression has
     exactly one parse tree.
   - `phase_op` is parameterized: `expr ⟴ R-1` is "marshal expr to
     ring -1"; `expr ⟵ @epoch(7)` is "merge into epoch 7."
   - `cap_op` similarly takes a parameter: `cap ⧈ acquire` /
     `cap ⧈ release` / `coherence ⧗ 0.94q`.
   - `comparison_op` is non-associative — `a < b < c` is a parse
     error (`PARSE-EXPR-002 chained comparisons`). Use explicit
     parentheses or compose via `⟁`.
   - `expr ⊗ glyph` materializes a Glyph at the current expression
     point; the `glyph` keyword is mandatory after `⊗` and
     disambiguates from cycle composition.
   - `cycle_invoke(IDENT, args)` is the canonical cycle-invocation
     form for cycles whose identity is content-addressed (looked up
     by mhash); ordinary calls use the `qualified_name(args)` form.
   - `sanctum.<method>(args)` is admissible only inside a
     `sanctum_enter` block. The parser admits the form unconditionally;
     the type system rejects it outside of `@sanctum_active` scope
     (`TYPE-SAN-001 sanctum method called outside sanctum frame`).
   - `irpd.<method>(args)` is the IRPD-discipline gateway for
     privileged writes (III-EFFECTS.md §2). The parser admits any
     method name; the type system enforces that only the 17 SE-kind
     methods are valid (`TYPE-IRPD-001 unknown irpd method`).
*)


(* ===================================================================
   §9. PATTERN PRODUCTIONS
   =================================================================== *)

pattern                 ::= literal_pattern
                          | ident_pattern
                          | wildcard_pattern
                          | tuple_pattern
                          | record_pattern
                          | hexad_pattern
                          | range_pattern
                          | path_pattern
                          | or_pattern
                          | guard_pattern

literal_pattern         ::= literal

ident_pattern           ::= IDENT                                   (* binding *)
                          | IDENT '@' pattern                       (* binding+nested match *)

wildcard_pattern        ::= '_'

tuple_pattern           ::= '(' pattern (',' pattern)* ')'
                          | '(' ')'

record_pattern          ::= qualified_name '{' record_pattern_field (',' record_pattern_field)* '}'

record_pattern_field    ::= IDENT ':' pattern
                          | IDENT                                   (* field-shorthand *)

hexad_pattern           ::= HEXAD_LIT
                          | '(' trit_pattern ',' trit_pattern ',' trit_pattern ',' trit_pattern ',' trit_pattern ',' trit_pattern ')'

trit_pattern            ::= TRIT_LIT
                          | '_'                                     (* wildcard trit *)

range_pattern           ::= literal '..' literal
                          | literal '..='  literal                  (* inclusive *)

path_pattern            ::= qualified_name '(' pattern (',' pattern)* ')'    (* tagged-variant *)
                          | qualified_name

or_pattern              ::= pattern ('|' pattern)+

guard_pattern           ::= pattern 'if' expr

(*
   Pattern-production commentary

   - `hexad_pattern` allows wildcard trits: `(POS, _, POS, _, _, _)`
     matches any hexad whose first and third trits are POS. This
     is essential for SID's classifier and for safety-routing in
     dispatch tables.
   - `range_pattern` covers integer and Q14 ranges. Mhash ranges
     (which appear in capability typing) use the `range` production
     in §6 rather than a literal pattern.
   - `or_pattern` (e.g., `NEG | POS`) is left-associative.
   - `guard_pattern` (`pat if cond`) is the only path to additional
     pattern conditions; the guard expression is admitted by §8.
*)


(* ===================================================================
   §10. DISAMBIGUATION RULES & ASSOCIATIVITY
   =================================================================== *)

(*
   §10.1 Generic vs Comparison

   The `<` and `>` punctuators serve dual roles. Disambiguation
   follows the rule: if a `<` appears immediately after a
   qualified_name in *type* context (post `:` or post `->`) or after
   the type-keywords `Cap`, `Cycle`, `Reduction`, `Uncertainty`,
   `CeilingMembership`, `MöbiusCoherence`, `Compromise`, then it
   begins a generic-args list; otherwise it is a comparison
   operator.

   In expression context, the parser uses a single-token lookahead:
   if the token following `<` is a *type-name* (uppercase identifier
   or primitive type name) and the closing `>` is found before any
   token that cannot occur inside a type-list, then it is a
   generic-args list; otherwise a comparison.

   §10.2 Cognitive Operator Right-Associativity

   `expr ⟐⟐ expr ⟐⟐ expr` parses as `expr ⟐⟐ (expr ⟐⟐ expr)`.
   This is intentional: deep self-reflection composes inward.

   §10.3 Trinity Gate Right-Associativity

   `intent ⟐ permission ⟐ causality` parses as
   `intent ⟐ (permission ⟐ causality)`. Trinity composes from the
   most-granular level (sanctum-state) outward to the most-abstract
   (intent), so right-association keeps the convergence point at
   the leftmost operand.

   §10.4 Phase Cross / Epoch Bridge Left-Associativity

   `value ⟴ R0 ⟴ R-1` is a parse error (`PARSE-EXPR-003 chained phase
   cross`); marshalling must traverse one ring at a time and is
   non-associative. Use explicit grouping: `((value ⟴ R0) ⟴ R-1)`.

   §10.5 Comparison Non-Associativity

   `a < b < c` is a parse error. Comparison operators are
   non-associative; this prevents the C/Python ambiguity where
   `a < b < c` could mean `(a < b) < c` (boolean compared to int).

   §10.6 Modifier Order Canonicalization

   When canonicalizing for R1 hashing (III-LEXICON.md §2.5), modifier
   sequences are sorted alphabetically by modifier name. The
   formatter `iii-fmt` performs this rewrite; the parser accepts any
   order. Two source files differing only in modifier order produce
   the same canonical form.

   §10.7 Block-Expression as Statement

   A `block_expr` may appear as `block_stmt` (with trailing `;`) or
   as the body of an `if`, `match`, `for`, or `while`. Inside a
   `block_expr`, the optional trailing `expr` (without `;`) is the
   block's value; without a trailing `expr`, the block has type
   `()` (unit).

   §10.8 Wavefront Body Sequencing

   Inside a `wavefront { ... } until X`, the contained statements
   are *not* required to be sequentially executed. They are admitted
   to the composed delta (per ACC Wall-Y, III-TRINITY.md §1.3 Layer
   2), and the runtime executes them in any order that satisfies the
   composed delta. Statement order in source is canonicalized by
   `iii-fmt --canonical-wavefront` to AST topological order
   (predecessor effects before successor effects). This rewrite is
   semantically equivalent and produces a stable canonical form.

   §10.9 Sanctum Frame Binding

   In `sanctum_enter |frame| { ... }`, the `frame` IDENT is bound to
   the per-CPU sanctum frame handle for the lexical scope of the
   block. The grammar does not admit elision of the `|frame|`; even
   if the frame is unused, the binder must be present (use `_` for
   the unused-binding case: `sanctum_enter |_| { ... }`).

   §10.10 Doc Comment Attachment

   A `DOC_COMMENT` token attaches to the syntactically next item
   (cycle / fn / type / mobius_candidate / schema / narrative /
   const / extern / use / module). A doc comment that does not
   attach (e.g., a doc comment after the last item before EOF) is
   rejected at parse time (`PARSE-DOC-001 dangling doc comment`).
*)


(* ===================================================================
   §11. AST KIND ENUMERATOR (iii_ast_kind_t)
   =================================================================== *)

(*
   Every production above corresponds to exactly one enumerator
   value in `iii_ast_kind_t`. The enumerator values are stable
   across grammar revisions; new productions added by Catalyst
   promotion (§13) are appended at the next available slot.

   The full enumerator (in `COMPILER/BOOT/ast.h`):

     enum iii_ast_kind_t {
         /* §4 — Module level */
         III_AST_MODULE                          = 0,
         III_AST_QUALIFIED_NAME                  = 1,
         III_AST_MODULE_ATTR                     = 2,
